{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":3688,"record_hash":"sha256:7fd43a3bfe86b3fc65f3ffd39656e2c16484d9fc24b2d90c9c6218d511835d85","timestamp":"2026-05-20T14:03:59.492Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 364862\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1553\nOutput:\n\n- `listSessions(project, filters, cursor)`: discovers sessions for handoff\n- `getSessionTimeline(session_key, window?)`: returns turn summaries plus\n  hydrated records for a bounded handoff window\n- `findRelatedSessions(target)`: returns scored session candidates with reason\n  objects and highlighted turn keys for review sharing\n- `getRelatedSessionDetail(target, session_key, turn_window, redaction_policy)`:\n  hydrates records around highlighted turns for a review surface\n- `previewReviewShare(target)`: returns what would be exposed before anything\n  leaves repo-private scope\n\nKeep those as read facades, not storage objects. They can evolve without\nrewriting turn metadata.\n\nFor handoff:\n\n1. read the project session index\n2. choose a session by recency, explicit selection, or relationship\n3. read session metadata, turns, and transcript records\n4. render records grouped by turn, or choose a recent turn window\n5. include environment snapshots only when useful for re-orientation\n\nFor review sharing:\n\n1. start from a branch, change, or PR\n2. use derived lookup indexes to find candidate turns and sessions\n3. resolve project-scoped sessions for those candidates\n4. read turns and observations for those sessions\n5. rank and explain the likely relationship from the underlying observations\n6. render the underlying transcript records for the selected windows\n\nFor a GitButler worktree with multiple applied branches, review sharing should\nbe able to show the whole associated session while highlighting the likely\nturns for the selected branch or PR. A narrower turn window can be selected\nlater without changing the session as the durable object.\n\nThe review product must not depend on a naive scan over all sessions and turns,\neven for the POC. The expected product query is:\n\n```text\ngiven a PR number or branch name, are there likely related agent sessions?\n```\n\nThat query needs an index-first read path. The system can \n[TRUNCATED]\n in `observed_targets`.\n\nDo not write a path index in v1. Path-level keys can explode with large commits,\nbroad worktree changes, generated files, or dependency lockfile churn. File\npaths remain in the turn observations for scoring after branch/review/change\ncandidate discovery.\n\nIndex entries are candidate discovery only. Readers must verify candidates by\nloading the referenced turn detail and checking that the queried branch, review,\nor change evidence is actually present before scoring. This keeps stale or\nobsolete index entries from becoming association truth.\n\nDo not implement index deletion or a rebuild command in v1. If key\ncanonicalization or index semantics change, bump the namespace from `v1` to a new\nversion and make readers use only the current namespace. Old index keys can\nremain as harmless derived metadata until a future pruning/rebuild mechanism is\nworth building.\n\nAdding indexes is not a large GitMeta model cost if they remain derived lookup\nkeys. The real costs are write amplification, stale-index rebuild behavior, key\nexplosion, sync bloat, and making sure readers do not treat\n`agentlog-index:*` as durable association truth.\n\nFor a branch-name query, lookup can start from turns where that branch was\nobserved in the stack/branch snapshot, then boost turns where commits on that\nbranch matched files from a previous worktree snapshot.\n\nFor a PR/review-id query, lookup can start from turns where a branch carried\nthat review identifier, then optionally expand through the PR branch, head\ncommits, change ids, and touched paths.\n\nFor read-time association scoring:\n\n1. find candidate turns from branch, review, or change indexes\n2. verify candidates against `TurnDetail.observed_targets`\n3. count observed branches/stacks/review units\n4. compare previous-turn worktree files with current-turn committed files\n5. rank candidate sessions, turns, changes, branches, and PRs\n6. return derived confidence, reasons, and highlighted turn windows without\n   writing a durable relationship\n\n## V1 Decision Details\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T14:03:59.492Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}